Inheritance in Java is a mechanism in which one object
acquires all the properties and behaviors of another class.

Why use inheritance in java
For Method Overriding (so runtime polymorphism can be achieved).
For Code Reusability.


Terms used in Inheritance

Class: A class is a group of objects which have common properties.
It is a template or blueprint from which objects are created.

Sub Class/Child Class: Subclass is a class which inherits the other class.
 It is also called a derived class, extended class, or child class.

Super Class/Parent Class: Superclass is the class
from where a subclass inherits the features. It is also called
a base class or a parent class.